In an interview with the Washington Post, press secretary Amelia Chess defended the governor’s actions, claiming that blocking comments is simply their moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and hackers who are harassing the internet.
Post spoke to some of the real people that Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls, -- a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their elected leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, substantive and not gross.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramana from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when many people leave comments on the same topic, some people immediately say it’s a so-called screwdriver, instead of admitting they’re dealing with a large group of dissatisfied citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life position.”
In the era of Facebook, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or clearing negative comments.
It is much less dusty work than before, when it was required to send people, collect and burn newspapers with critical advances, or arrest and shut up protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening right now, just in the figure.
