And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin has filed complaints by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal expenses made roughly the same turnaround as today’s Internet.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers had quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters greatly overthrew his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Porcius" wrote letters in newspapers that ridiculed Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the online project “George Washington’s Documents,” his office was shattered by petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Maritime Affairs.
But he didn’t try to keep them silent.
Freedom of speech, dissension and speech is at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing with that.
