Haftar carried out operations on the other front, Benghazi.
And with ISIS in Sirte were fighting structures that were subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited people to Russia who carried out this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation received in the Council of the Federation, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Rosgardia.
You, as we understand, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the moods of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections that were reached in late July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has been the case several times in the past, will the agreements be broken, the hostilities resume, the parties will try to take power unilaterally?
For us a good signal has already been the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to meet again, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have reacted extremely negatively to each other.
As for Russia’s position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misurata, and it was on that day that Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurata they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is precisely to show: we are not only supporting Haftar, we are conducting a dialogue with all the key actors in the Libyan conflict.
You and Haftar talked.
Does understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level make it easier for him to study in the USSR twice?
And, by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
Russian, if you know it, is relative.
But what he has learned from us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misurata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or still in the Soviet Union.
And that's why they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent experiencing nostalgia on it.
Do you think it is likely that the arms embargo imposed against Libya will be repealed immediately?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have already said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm one another to the detriment of the other.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As far as the arms embargo is concerned, there are constant calls from Libyans for Russia to somehow facilitate its withdrawal.
Libya is now actively advancing the process of drafting a constitution.
We hope that the parties will come to compromise decisions, that they will reach an internal consensus.
Then the elections, as discussed at the meeting between Sarajevo and Haftar, must take place.
If elections are held and a legitimate power is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be put in the UN Security Council.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to a escalation of the conflict.
It has been reported in the media that Italy, facing the problem of floating African refugees from Libya, feels thrown into the hands of EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using their ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is it that the Haftar troops will establish control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers relocating immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia’s support, because Moscow is simultaneously in dialogue with Haftar, Sarajevo, Misurata and the south of the country.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a major role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the Southerners intercepting the flows of migrants on long-distance footpaths?
I mean, conditionally speaking, were the buses back-to-back that Nigerian migrants are going to take?
