But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these streams going.
We hope to help bring the South together in the negotiating process between Sarajevo, Haftar and the tribes of the South.
But first, we would like to see the unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarajevo.
The head of government in Tripoli Faiz Saraj is considered an Islamist, a proponent of the country's introduction of sharia rules.
How radical is it that he holds?
Wouldn’t that be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give you my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he, on the contrary, is an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country – a moderately Islamic, open world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
How did he get such a reputation?
It is created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, there is legislative, executive and judiciary power.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in not letting us down there.
And we mixed them all the cards and started actively communicating with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And let us reap the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded an agreement on cooperation with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rossnefti chief Igor Sechin made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago there was the first shipment of Libyan oil company Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess to resell.
What are the economic interests of Russia in Libya?
It plans to re-sign the contracts concluded with Muammar Gaddafi.
These include, in particular, previous agreements in the transport sector (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Is there anything the Libyans can pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, as in the case of Iran, is it about the “petroleum in exchange for services” scheme?
I don’t know what the scheme will be, I don’t directly deal with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We're actually doing peacekeeping work there.
For us, the most important thing is to stop the bloodshed, help the Libyans to come to terms with each other so that they can establish order and that Libya ceases to be a favourable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task – to help the Libyan people and to push out terrorists from there.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to clarify this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to this day no one from Russia or other countries of the former Soviet Union is there.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "I") and the Russian language doesn't sound there.
What countries are these fighters from?
I don't want to go into those details.
Let's formulate the question differently.
How many militants in Libya are the Libyans themselves?
There are almost no Libyans among them, no more than 5%.
The rest are here.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan negotiations on the example of Paris?
There are plans like that.
We are conducting active negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and expressed their willingness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say now.
There are still a few more visits to take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of negotiations.
