The history of Scotty Castle has not been studied much since the National Fund received full access to it only in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassi, died.
When Rods arrived ten years later, the staff only began to deal with the archive, which he describes as "what the aristocrats had fallen to the ground for centuries."
The diaries, the letters of the British Empire's times, the maps showing who owned something: "You think the land disputes are boring," says Rods, "but two families fought for this pond.
“That’s right, guys!”
In some stories the castle collection becomes the starting point for broader quests in English history: for example, in the Worker's, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is information about the uprising that took place at the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex," Rods said.
“The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought the uprising was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?”
Other plots are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells the story of a Jesuit priest whom the Darrel family had been hiding for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Contrabandist", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funerals by stamping the tomb with stones (this was discovered several years later when the tomb was excavated).
Darrell is the beloved Rods family of all Scots people: "The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect villain, always indebted and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
