Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease CVD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies say the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those who suffer from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and swelling of the abdomen, chronic or blood cough, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Leading researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestine ensure that the harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of initiating an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and not damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severely disrupted in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with certain bacteria in their intestines appear to increase cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of the protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have found a link between one type of bacteria — Lactobacillus reuteri — that is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in the diet of mice, the more these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to intestinal inflammation.
Postdoc Dr. Luiza Cervantes-Barraghanvas, studying the variety of immune cell-enhancing cells, found that one group of rats tested had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line but contained them separately.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the microbiome of the gut of mice — the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the gut cells of mice were sequencing, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells, but absent in mice without them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the liquid — free of bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
Immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of tryptophan, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice’s food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were reduced by two, the number of cells also dropped by two.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same cell-enhancing tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as well as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in tryptophan-related genes have been detected.
She says, “Maybe we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may potentially lead to an increase in their population.”
