The White House's record was worth thousands of dollars to taxpayers
According to records of the armed forces provided by TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to deploy a Marine helicopter to the South Lakes at an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers 24,000 dollars.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the "Marine One", when the president is on board, became a central element of the July 17 White House event demonstrating American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials have inspected tech products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was exhibited next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for the management of the helicopter, the Military Administration of the White House ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO" order, just 36 hours before the helicopter.
“I just wanted you to make sure you are aware of it because it’s an unusual event that is widely illuminated in the press,” the commander of the HMX-1 wrote in an email to his chief, the first deputy chief of the air force of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Strait at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in the event scheduled for 3 a.m., and will remain there until the lawn will be released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on working hours.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether the second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal officials from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event was not contrary to this decision.
“We asked, among other things, if it was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“You don’t seem to have a place to go,” replied the deputy chief.
The event “Made in America” was declared by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote the health reform, which was then being drafted in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travelling.
But asking them only for the sake of photography is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane was flying in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was shattered by messages with complaints about the use of the presidential plane ahead of his predecessor.
"The White House is thrilled with the 'Made in America' show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers made of American materials," White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsey Walters said in a statement.
The HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Pole to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the event “Made in America” was calculated for the crew in the account of the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours on that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not pay the expenses for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lake.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of Defence for the fiscal year 2017, the VH-3D compensation rate for the Ministry of Defence is <0x24>24,380 per flight hour.
It is recorded in the records of the unit that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its base airport at the Quantico Marine Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“Calculating the cost for taxpayers on the basis of an approximate rate of reimbursement is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These exemplary rates include personal composition, service, and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual allocations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the REND Corporation, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was in favour of using the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to showcase things done in America this week,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
Therefore, of course, it is appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump was interacting with the helicopter while inspecting the South Side during the event, but he was definitely sitting in the driver’s seat in the fire car.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” said the president. “I have three of them.”
